@node Command line version of R, R.app, Building R from sources, Top
@chapter Command line version of R

The command line version of @R{} is almost identical to @R{} as used on
other Unix-like operating systems. Therefore general documentation for
@R{} applies to this version as well.  On each release ready-to-use
binaries are distributed through @CRAN{}.  These binaries come with a
common installer used by @Rapp{} so please read the related notes
(@pxref{How to get R.app}).

On recent versions of OS X (Snow Leopard and later) the installer links
three executables in @file{/usr/bin}, @code{R32}, @code{R64} and
@code{R}.  The first is 32-bit, the second is 64-bit and @code{R} is
64-bit on Snow Leopard and Lion and later but 32-bit on Leopard (and on
Mountain Lion for 2.15.2 and earlier).  It also links @code{Rscript} (of
the same default architecture as @code{R}).

One thing that is different from @R{} on any other Unix-like is the way
output is displayed on a terminal.  Except for `dumb' terminals,
messages to @file{stderr} are diverted to @file{stdout} and displayed in
bold using ANSI terminal escapes.

@c links to /usr/bin/R these days.
@c To use @R{} you probably need to add a symbolic link on your system as
@c the @R{} binary is located inside the framework.  Suppose you have the
@c @emph{/usr/local/bin} directory on your system (if you do not have one,
@c you can use @emph{/usr/bin} instead) you should just type in your
@c Terminal (a root password is required)
@c @example
@c sudo ln -s /Library/Frameworks/R.framework/Resources/R /usr/local/bin/R
@c @end example
@c Assuming that you have @emph{/usr/local/bin} in your @emph{PATH}
@c environment variable, you will be able to launch R from any location on
@c your system just by typing @emph{R}. In this way, when you install a new
@c version of the @emph{R.framework} this link will point to the latest R
@c binary.

